{"key":"post-12384279","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12384279</id>\n<content>Adding a casing layer to half a substrate and leaving the other half uncased is like taking both wheels off the passenger side of a car to see if the wheeled side works better than the unwheeled side.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The only legitimate way to experiment with this is to case ten to twenty substrates, and leave ten to twenty uncased.&amp;nbsp; Then compare yields and performance, averaged over the whole lot.&amp;nbsp; I've done this many times and is the reason I started saying a few years ago that a casing layer is of little to no benefit to cubensis growing on bulk substrates.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The fact is, cubensis isn't among the species that require a casing layer.&amp;nbsp; Other species such as agaricus(button mushrooms) won't fruit in captivity without one.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12384300</next>\n<prev>12384146</prev>\n<first>12377916</first>\n<last>12384380</last>\n<when>1271174085</when>\n<utime>04/13/10 06:54 PM</utime>\n</post>"}